                                    1250    (Central Europe)
                                    1251    (Cyrillic)
                                    1252    (Latin I)
                                    1253    (Greek)
                                    1254    (Turkish)
                                    1255    (Hebrew)
                                    1256    (Arabic)
                                    1257    (Baltic)
                                    1258    (Vietnam)
            <DegreeChar>        (Optional; default=94) The code point / glyph index of the degree glyph. This number must be in base-10 (NOT hexadecimal).
            <DiameterChar>      (Optional; default=216) The code point / glyph index of the diameter glyph. This number must be in base-10 (NOT hexadecimal).
            <PlusMinusChar>     (Optional; default=200) The code point / glyph index of the plus/minus glyph. This number must be in base-10 (NOT hexadecimal).
            <NamedSymbols>      (Optional) One or more <NamedSymbol> nodes (see below) that allow you to define named code points for custom glyphs in fonts.
            <CreateShxUnifont>  (Optional; default=True) When converting to DWG, controls whether a Unifont (vs. old locale-encoded) is created when converting RSC fonts.
                                The only time this should be False is for symbol fonts, which re-purpose code points to be custom symbols, and thus Unicode re-mapping is useless.
                                Must be one of True|False.
            
            <NamedSymbol>
                <Key>           (Required) A non-localized string that identifies this symbol across cultures.
                                The following are reserved for internal use: "Degree", "Diameter", "PlusMinus".
                <DisplayName>   (Required*) The name of the symbol; this will be displayed in pickers.
                                This is required for all user-defined symbols; Bentley-delivered symbols rely on a hard-coded lookup based on their <Key> for localization purposes.
                <CodePoint>     (Required) The code point / glyph index of the symbol. This number must be in base-10 (NOT hexadecimal).
        -->

